It wouldn't have been enough at that stage; the Japanese still wanted to hang onto Korea, the
Kuriles, Karafuto (Southern Sakhalin), and Manchuko at the very least, no Allied Occupation,
Japanese supvervision of demobilization, and Japan trying War Criminals. Those were
definite non-starters as far as Truman was concerned. "You can keep the Emperor, but
everything else we reject" would have been the line drawn. With that, there's no avoiding
15 Kt on Hiroshima, and 20 Kt on Nagasaki, not to mention the Soviet Invasion of Manchuria
that the Japanese feared, but in their "cloud-cookoo land" felt was a year away. Three
Soviet Army Groups on 9 Aug swept such delusions aside, along with the Kwantung Army.
